  "prompt": "I confessed my feelings to my crush and she became very angry. What should I do?",
  "response": "I'm really sorry to hear that you're going through this difficult experience. Confessing your feelings takes a lot of courage, and it's understandable to feel hurt when the response isn't what you hoped for. Here are a few steps you might consider:\n\n1. **Give Her Space:** Sometimes, when emotions run high, people need time to process their feelings. Giving her some space can help both of you calm down and gain perspective on the situation.\n\n2. **Reflect on the Interaction:** Think about the conversation and try to understand what might have triggered her reaction. Was there something specific you said or did that could have upset her? Reflecting can provide insights for future interactions.\n\n3. **Communicate Openly:** If you feel it's appropriate and after some time has passed, consider reaching out to have an open and honest conversation. Express that your intention was to be sincere and that you value her feelings and perspective.\n\n4. **Respect Her Feelings:** It's important to acknowledge and respect her emotions, even if they're difficult to handle. Everyone processes feelings differently, and her initial reaction might not fully represent her long-term feelings.\n\n5. **Take Care of Yourself:** Rejection or negative reactions can be emotionally taxing. Make sure to take care of your own emotional well-being by talking to friends, engaging in activities you enjoy, or seeking support if needed.\n\n6. **Move Forward Gradually:** Depending on how things unfold, you might need to adjust your expectations or the nature of your relationship moving forward. This can take time, and that's okay.\n\nRemember, it's natural to feel a range of emotions in this situation. Surround yourself with supportive people and give both yourself and her the time needed to navigate through this experience.",
